  "prompt": "What integer solutions to x and y are there for 167x+113y=1?",
  "response": "The equation \\(167x + 113y = 1\\) is a linear Diophantine equation. Such an equation has integer solutions if and only if the greatest common divisor (GCD) of the coefficients of \\(x\\) and \\(y\\) divides the constant term on the right-hand side. Since the right-hand side is 1, we only need to check whether \\(\\gcd(167, 113) = 1\\) to confirm that solutions exist. \n\n167 and 113 are both prime numbers, meaning they have no common divisors other than 1, so \\(\\gcd(167, 113) = 1\\). This confirms that there are integer solutions to the equation.\n\nTo find one particular solution, we can use the Extended Euclidean Algorithm, which finds integer solutions to equations of the form \\(ax + by = \\gcd(a, b)\\).\n\nLet's apply the Euclidean Algorithm to 167 and 113:\n\n1. Divide 167 by 113:\n   \\[\n   167 = 1 \\times 113 + 54\n   \\]\n\n2. Divide 113 by 54:\n   \\[\n   113 = 2 \\times 54 + 5\n   \\]\n\n3. Divide 54 by 5:\n   \\[\n   54 = 10 \\times 5 + 4\n   \\]\n\n4. Divide 5 by 4:\n   \\[\n   5 = 1 \\times 4 + 1\n   \\]\n\n5. Divide 4 by 1:\n   \\[\n   4 = 4 \\times 1 + 0\n   \\]\n\nNow, we perform the back substitution to express 1 as a linear combination of 167 and 113:\n\nStarting with \\(1 = 5 - 1 \\times 4\\), substitute from the step where we expressed 4:\n\n\\[\n1 = 5 - 1 \\times (54 - 10 \\times 5) = 11 \\times 5 - 1 \\times 54\n\\]\n\nNext, substitute from the step where we expressed 5:\n\n\\[\n1 = 11 \\times (113 - 2 \\times 54) - 1 \\times 54 = 11 \\times 113 - 22 \\times 54 - 1 \\times 54 = 11 \\times 113 - 23 \\times 54\n\\]\n\nFinally, substitute from where we expressed 54:\n\n\\[\n1 = 11 \\times 113 - 23 \\times (167 - 1 \\times 113) = 11 \\times 113 - 23 \\times 167 + 23 \\times 113 = 34 \\times 113 - 23 \\times 167\n\\]\n\nThus, one particular solution is \\(x = -23\\), \\(y = 34\\).\n\nThe general solution to the equation is given by:\n\\[\nx = -23 + 113t, \\quad y = 34 - 167t\n\\]\nwhere \\(t\\) is any integer. Each value of \\(t\\) will provide a different integer solution to the original equation.",
